This is the most Detroit-y pizza I have ever had -  Yearly family visit to the original Buddy's Pizza on Conant Street has seemed to permanently ruin my opinion of most other pizza - but at last!!! Found my new spot.
Does this restaurant care about how it treats its customers anymore? The staff here was so rude... to the point of absurdity, it was almost comical. I will never come here again.

They have deep dish Detroit style pizza. We had the vegan pizza; it was pretty good. We ordered cocktails that tasted like they had no alcohol in them at all. Not to mention, the cocktails are really expensive! For the price I'm paying, I'd expect a well crafted drink.  Very overpriced for the quality of the drinks and service.

I ordered two pizzas on Super Bowl night, figuring that would be enough for four people. I ordered via phone for pickup and was told it would be a 45 min wait. I arrived 45 minutes later, but It took over 90 minutes before my pizza was ready. I wasn’t terribly annoyed by this bc I noticed the restaurant was short-staffed. One hostess was frantically trying to accommodate all the orders as they were coming in. The pizza itself was delicious; my partner is from Detroit & said it tasted just like Detroit pizza. However, the pizzas were incredibly small for the amount I paid. I normally don’t complain about food being overpriced because good quality food is worth the extra $$, but in this case it is warranted. I spent $40 on just 8 slices of pizza. The slices aren’t big, either. Fortunately, we had other food to keep ourselves fed during the game.
Pizza crust was nice but everything else was bad. Overpriced with cheap ingredients that manages to be both too salty and tasteless at the same time.

Pretty solid place over all. The bartender Twan* (sp;  or Twon) is the best--super conversational, friendly, real chill, makes a good drink and will fix it for you if it isn't to your liking. Music is always dope--usually an alternative R&B/Hip Hop/Old school/lo-fi kind of feel, great for blipsters and folks that like quality music. Happy hour prices are good too.  I will say though--had the worst whiskey sour of my life yesterday during happy hour. It was the one day i've come to this bar and *Twan/Twon wasn't working. The other bartender put waaaaay too much sour mix and not enough whiskey. Then when I asked him to fix it, he basically added nothing to it. Had my date taste it and she felt the same. ::smh:: Gonna go see *Twan/Twon on Mondays at Bin 1301 and see what days he's working at Red Light so I don't have to deal with the bad drinks again.

This is a small little bar on 14th street in the Logan Circle area. This is a great place to go if you are not wanting a big crowd after get done with work during the week. They have outdoor seating and you go up to a window to order food/drinks when lounging outside. In addition, they have decent happy hour specials and fried gnocchi which is such a great concept -- being from Missouri, it reminds me of fried ravioli. Most importantly, they have a diverse beer selection that will please even the craft beer snob. I recommend this place if you are looking for a quick place to enjoy an evening and talk with friends.

The ambiance at red light is awesome, great outdoor seating and cool indoor vibes. That being said, I waited 35 minutes for a plate of hummus with naan, and a caprese panini. When my order arrived, the sand which was wrong, which entailed another 15 minute wait. The hummus was delicious, I definitely recommend. The caprese panini was beyond disappointing..... I don't know how you can mess up a 3 ingredient sandwich, but apparently it's possible. The manager did put my sandwich on the house which was appreciated. Overall meh experience that made me want to leave asap.

I stopped in last weekend during Red Light's soft opening and our party of 4 was seated quickly on the crowded patio on Saturday evening. Granted, it was drizzling, but the staff were pleasant, accommodating, and settled us comfortably under the sturdy covered awning. Service was stellar across the board - friendly and funny without being too familiar. The dessert selection was lovely - out of 10 or so offerings, at least 3-4 involved chocolate (DARK chocolate, the server emphasized). My favorite: the black and tan beignets. Chocolate soufflé and Mexican chocolate torte were also delicious. From the drink menu, we ordered a few Cake Shakes, which were sweet and indulgent - though the glasses were suspiciously loaded more with ice cubes and less with beverage. A more favorable shake-to-ice ratio would've earned this place the extra star... for now, a solid four-star start to this welcome addition to 14th!
